<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-043-016 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 323 437</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Shopper  Oct 1991 v11 n10 p135(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Borland and Ashton-Tate tie the knot; creating Conan-sizeddatabase force. (Borland International Inc. and Ashton-Tate merge)(Trends andamp; Technology)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Borland International Inc. (Acquisitions, mergers, divestments)Ashton-Tate Corp. (Acquisitions, mergers, divestments).andO;Ticker:    TATE; BORLN.andO;Topic:     MergerSoftware PublishersData Base Management SystemsAcquisitionMarketing Strategy.andO;Feature:   illustrationportrait.andO;Caption:   Philippe Kahn. (portrait)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Borland chief Philippe Kahn likes to jest that his company is the truebarbarian of the software field.andP;  Humor aside, the French-born entrepreneuris flexing new and impressive muscle in the database software market.andM;By moving to acquire its chief competitor, Ashton-Tate, in a $439 millionstock swap, Borland will become the dominant supplier of databaseapplications and the third-largest maker of PC software behind Microsoft andLotus.andP;  The acquisition brings together Ashton-Tate's dBASE and Borland;sParadox--the two best-selling databases in the market.andM;&quot;We're going to be an exciting company, from a stockholder standpoint, from atechnical standpoint, and from a customer standpoint,&quot; said Kahn.andM;The first thing he'll have to do is figure out what to do with two competingproduct lines.andP;  Borland has committed itself to protecting customerinvestments in each company's products, as well as providing &quot;smoothmigration paths to future technologies.&quot;andM;Ashton-Tate, once the undisputed leader in its market, had been plaqued bylosses, layoffs, and dropping market share resulting from delays and bugs inits dBASE line that began three years ago.andP;  As dBASE's market share slipped,Borland began offering Paradox at deep discounts to Ashton-Tate users.andM;However, under IBM veteran William Lyons, who succeeded Ed Esber last year asAshton-Tate CEO, the company had taken steps to right itself.andP;  Now it'sBorland's turn to hold center stage, and the bulked-up presence of thissoftware Conan will likely cause more than a little discomfort to itscompetitors.andO;</TEXT></DOC>